ntent of laughter, disgust, and even empathy. Northwestern University's most popular professor, Morson attributes declining student interest in literature to current teaching methods. He argues in favor of showing how literature fosters empathy with people unlike ourselves. Ever playful, Morson explores the relation of games to wit, which expresses the power of the mind to triumph over contingency in the social world.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmpathy in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEvents (Philosophy) in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aFictionxHistory and criticism. 0aProse literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aBethea, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChudo, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aNational Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Programefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618116758zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618116758zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618116758/original  a978-3-11-068814-6 Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA